05019nam a22007695i 9780813572406DE-B159720191126113341.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191126s2015    nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135724067 a10.36019/97808135724062doi  a(DE-B1597)536706  a(OCoLC)908040531  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aE184.36.P64 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a973/.049242231 aGurock, Jeffrey S., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Holocaust Averted :bAn Alternate History of American Jewry, 1938-1967 /cJeffrey S. Gurock. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2015] 4cÂ©2015  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments / rGurock, Jeffrey S. -- tPrologue: Ghosts in the Restored Jewish Quarter in Krakow: An Entrance into Alternate Jewish History -- t1. A World at War, 1938 -- t2. American Jewry in the Late 1930s: A Respite for an Insecure Community -- t3. Conflicting Challenges for an America at Peace, 1938-1944 -- t4. Without the "Boss": American Jewry's Concerns, 1940-1944 -- t5. The Eastern European Threat and an End to U.S. Isolationism, 1944-1945 -- t6. Divided Allegiances: American Jews and Israel, 1944-1950 -- t7. Suburban Jewish Cul de Sacs, 1950-1960 -- t8. The 1960s and the Trials of Acceptance for American Jews -- t9. Unending Dilemmas: Israelis, Arabs, the World Powers, and American Jews -- tConclusion: Alternate History and the Realities of American Jewish Life -- tNotes -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe increasingly popular genre of "alternative histories" has captivated audiences by asking questions like "what if the South had won the Civil War?" Such speculation can be instructive, heighten our interest in a topic, and shed light on accepted history. In The Holocaust Averted, Jeffrey Gurock imagines what might have happened to the Jewish community in the United States if the Holocaust had never occurred and forces readers to contemplate how the road to acceptance and empowerment for today's American Jews could have been harder than it actually was.   Based on reasonable alternatives grounded in what is known of the time, places, and participants, Gurock presents a concise narrative of his imagined war-time saga and the events that followed Hitler's military failures. While German Jews did suffer under Nazism, the millions of Jews in Eastern Europe survived and were able to maintain their communities. Since few people were concerned with the safety of European Jews, Zionism never became popular in the United States and social antisemitism kept Jews on the margins of society. By the late 1960s, American Jewish communities were far from vibrant. This alternate history-where, among many scenarios, Hitler is assassinated, Japan does not bomb Pearl Harbor, and Franklin Delano Roosevelt is succeeded after two terms by Robert A. Taft-does cause us to review and better appreciate history. As Gurock tells his tale, he concludes every chapter with a short section that describes what actually happened and, thus, further educates the reader.        aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Nov 2019) 0aArab-Israeli conflictxInfluence. 0aIsrael and the diaspora. 0aJewzUnited StatesxIdentity. 0aJewszUnited StatesxAttitudes toward Israel. 0aJewszUnited StatesxPolitics and governmenty20th century. 0aZionismzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 70(DE-601)10430670X0(DE-588)4028808-0aJuden2gnd 70(DE-601)1048262900(DE-588)4041158-8aNahostkonflikt2gnd 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813572406423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813572406.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEB